      "solution": "import sys\n\ninput()\nvalues = list(map(int, input().split()))\nheight = values.copy()\n\ngrid, maxlength, curheight, finalheight, minheight = [], 0, 0, -1, min(min(height),0)\nif minheight < 0:\n    height = [ x - minheight + 1 for x in height ] \n    if values[-1] < 0: height += [-minheight + 1]     # handling mountain with negative height at end\n    if values[0] < 0 : height = [-minheight + 1] + height     # handling mountain with negative height at start\n    curheight, finalheight = -minheight + 1, -minheight\n    grid = [\"\" for x in range(-minheight + 1)]\n\nwhile height:\n    cur = height.pop(0)\n\n    for i in range(curheight, cur):\n        if len(grid) > i: grid[i] += \" \" * ( maxlength- len(grid[i])) + \"/\"\n        else: grid.append(\" \" * maxlength + \"/\") \n        maxlength += 1\n    curheight = cur-1\n    \n    nextheight = finalheight if not height else min(height[0]-2,cur-2)\n    for i in range(curheight, nextheight, -1):\n        grid[i] += \" \"*( maxlength- len(grid[i])) +\"\\\\\"\n        maxlength+=1\n    curheight = nextheight+1\n\n    # Debugging for each step\n    [print(x, file=sys.stderr) for x in grid[::-1]] + [print(\"-------------\", file=sys.stderr)]\n\n[print(x) for x in grid[::-1]]",
      "statement": "\"We don't make mistakes, just happy little accidents.\" - Bob Ross\n\nWhile creating mountains in ASCII, you realized that taller mountains could start off from the smaller ones,  so why not make some more mountains?\n\n\n\n<<Rules:>>\n\n- You will be given a list of the heights of mountain peaks along a row.\n\n- The starting height is considered as 0. \n\n- Each step of rise in altitude is represented by '/' and fall by '\\'.\n\n- Each peak consists of a rise and fall '/\\' at the appropriate height.\n\n- Once a peak has been drawn, proceed either up or down to the next peak. Do not return to 0 between peaks.  \n\n- After generating the mountains, end at height 0.\n\n- You may need to draw below 0. Remember, mountains are made from a step lower than their peak. Example, for [[-1]] :\n`\\    /   \n \\/\\/` which demonstrates the tip of the mountain at -1 height, given that the starting and ending point are at height 0.\n\n\nThis is an extension of \"Mountain Map\": https://www.codingame.com/ide/puzzle/mountain-map",
